<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="describe_structure_function_arterioles_metarterioles_capillaries_venules_lbd_01"><title>DynaDrop Assessment</title><page id="a91f971a940a4fdb891daf29a04321ac"><title>Page 1</title><question id="q1"><body><p id="fe0cf181a58845d1ab9867b0252d77ce">Match each vessel type with the appropriate description.</p><custom id="dragDrop" src="../../../webcontent/DynaDropHTML.js" type="javascript" width="550" height="200" layout="../webcontent/describe_structure_function_arterioles_metarterioles_capillaries_venules_lbd_01_layout.xml" logging="true"><cite id="ic2fee168542847fdb540dba72d1a76e0" /><caption /><popout enable="false" /><param name="showInputs">false</param></custom></body><fill_in_the_blank id="Init_arteriole" shuffle="true"><choice value="Location1">Location1</choice><choice value="Location2">Location2</choice><choice value="Location3">Location3</choice><choice value="Location4">Location4</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="Init_metarteriole" shuffle="true"><choice value="Location1">Location1</choice><choice value="Location2">Location2</choice><choice value="Location3">Location3</choice><choice value="Location4">Location4</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="Init_capillary" shuffle="true"><choice value="Location1">Location1</choice><choice value="Location2">Location2</choice><choice value="Location3">Location3</choice><choice value="Location4">Location4</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank id="Init_venule" shuffle="true"><choice value="Location1">Location1</choice><choice value="Location2">Location2</choice><choice value="Location3">Location3</choice><choice value="Location4">Location4</choice></fill_in_the_blank><part id="eb08823227cb4d85800c414c27987394"><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_venules_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_capillaries_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_metarterioles_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_arterioles_SKILL" /><response input="Init_arteriole" match="Location1" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae92b1ed80fda4948bf82d1cfdb7dbec9">Incorrect. Arterioles have all 3 vessel layers.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_arteriole" match="Location2" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae85484e4cc554a48a018bc59f4c048e8">Incorrect. Arterioles dilate during inflammation, but are not the site of white blood cells exiting the vascular compartment.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_arteriole" match="Location3" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab460f49f35f443d0b338677cca869e38">Incorrect. Arterioles are important regulators of blood flow, but do not adjust flow at the individual capillary level.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_arteriole" match="Location4" score="10"><feedback><p id="aea3a4dc2d6e145eb8deb8302269cb8ba">Correct. Arterioles can dilate or constrict in response to various nervous, hormonal or local signaling molecules as a way of diverting blood toward, or away from, tissues.</p></feedback></response><hint><p id="aa71a7121d29645ff80248abb84c379f3">Since arterioles can respond to different local signals, they can perform a certain function.</p></hint></part><part id="ad5565b5207e449e8fc45f71d9e56102"><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_venules_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_capillaries_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_metarterioles_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_arterioles_SKILL" /><response input="Init_metarteriole" match="Location1" score="0"><feedback><p id="afbb1ddea9ff04790a99fd86c8b7948dd">Incorrect. Metarterioles do not have a tunica media, but have the other 2 layers.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_metarteriole" match="Location2" score="0"><feedback><p id="add03b2aafc4a45c1bb31206cf7ec6fe7">Incorrect. Metarterioles would open their precapillary sphincters during inflammation, but they are not the site of white blood cells exiting the vascular compartment.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_metarteriole" match="Location3" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad60d2ac6642c427c82cd78cfb592c243">Correct. Metarterioles contain precapillary sphincters that can adjust flow to individual capillaries.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_metarteriole" match="Location4" score="0"><feedback><p id="abaa4c2c1b1cd4464b26155032950fb45">Incorrect. Metarterioles contain precapillary sphincters that control flow at the individual capillary level, not at a whole tissue level.</p></feedback></response><hint><p id="aff11bb7f44344c1fbeabc9a87eb52471">Precapillary sphincters allow metarterioles to perform a certain function.</p></hint></part><part id="a8ead7ac4fb149c88b9b64723748fdfd"><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_venules_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_capillaries_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_metarterioles_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_arterioles_SKILL" /><response input="Init_capillary" match="Location1" score="10"><feedback><p id="adab4164e83504fa4943c66b0a54ae393">Correct. Capillaries are best adapted for nutrient exchange, and a single thin layer benefits this by keeping diffusion distances short.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_capillary" match="Location2" score="0"><feedback><p id="adb59a72c67b6497f839d517391a5d5f2">Incorrect. Capillaries participate in exchange of most materials, but are not the most common site of white blood cell exit.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_capillary" match="Location3" score="0"><feedback><p id="aec3942aaabe9403f98ab903278bb5298">Incorrect. Capillaries cannot control flow to themselves.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_capillary" match="Location4" score="0"><feedback><p id="af50eafa6b9ed4ee0a3ba2499372427a1">Incorrect. Capillaries do not regulate flow to tissues.</p></feedback></response><hint><p id="ac211e722b52d4013a858ea60d96aade0">Having only a single layer benefits capillaries in nutrient exchange by minimizing diffusion distance.</p></hint></part><part id="f99aa20054d04933b993521515ad4430"><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_venules_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_capillaries_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_metarterioles_SKILL" /><skillref idref="describe_structure_function_arterioles_SKILL" /><response input="Init_venule" match="Location1" score="0"><feedback><p id="afc190643087f44359523307d895321a9">Incorrect. Venules have thin walls, but they still contain all three layers.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_venule" match="Location2" score="10"><feedback><p id="ae08d676c9b274faeafe43127dc2a8b53">Correct. The smallest of the venules are porous enough during the inflammatory process to allow white blood cells to leave the vasculature and move into the tissues.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_venule" match="Location3" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad059cf7aad484d58b4787c66f22546e7">Incorrect. Venules are distal to capillaries and therefore cannot control flow into them.</p></feedback></response><response input="Init_venule" match="Location4" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad0f661e2fe5d42feba2bb12b3b41f596">Incorrect. Venules start the return path of blood to the heart and are not involved in distributing blood to tissues.</p></feedback></response><hint><p id="aedb75805233e44ca93f84838b4c221eb">The smallest venules are able to carry out a certain process because they are porous.</p></hint></part></question></page></assessment>
